\bye

%%%%%%stuff originally at end of section II:
We have also
calculated the two-derivative term at finite temperature to make
sure that it is well behaved (\ie positive)
below and above the critical temperature.

Finally, let us remark that in 3+1 dimensions the effective potential is
$$
\veff^{(3+1)}={1\over32\pi^2}\left(2\La^2m^2+m^4{\log(m^2/\La^2)}-
{m^4\over2}\right).
$$
It is, as mentioned above, much more divergent than in 2+1 dimensions:
quadratically rather than linear. This is a serious problem
if one hopes to attain
large-$N$ renormalizability,\refto{roswarpar} as discussed above.




